You can parallel-test broken links in Java using:

Streams (parallelStream)
ExecutorService (ThreadPool)
CompletableFuture
RestAssured

Below is the cleanest and most practical explanation + examples.

âœ… 1. Parallel Broken-Link Check using parallelStream() (Easiest)
List<String> urls = List.of(
        "https://google.com",
        "https://example.com/wrong",
        "https://openai.com"
);

urls.parallelStream().forEach(url -> {
    try {
        HttpURLConnection con = (HttpURLConnection) new URL(url).openConnection();
        con.setRequestMethod("GET");
        con.setConnectTimeout(5000);
        con.connect();

        int code = con.getResponseCode();
        System.out.println(url + " -> " + code);
    } catch (Exception e) {
        System.out.println(url + " -> BROKEN (" + e.getMessage() + ")");
    }
});

âœ” Why this works?

Each URL is executed in parallel

Java decides the thread count

Best for quick link checks

âœ… 2. Using ThreadPool (ExecutorService) â€” More Control
ExecutorService pool = Executors.newFixedThreadPool(10);

List<String> urls = List.of("https://google.com", "https://wrongurl.com");

for (String url : urls) {
    pool.submit(() -> {
        try {
            HttpURLConnection con = (HttpURLConnection) new URL(url).openConnection();
            con.setRequestMethod("GET");
            con.setConnectTimeout(5000);
            con.connect();

            int code = con.getResponseCode();
            System.out.println(url + " -> " + code);
        } catch (Exception e) {
            System.out.println(url + " -> BROKEN");
        }
    });
}

pool.shutdown();

âœ” Why use this?

Control number of threads

Perfect for testing 500+ links

âœ… 3. Using CompletableFuture (Best + Very Fast)
List<String> urls = List.of("https://google.com", "https://openai.com");

List<CompletableFuture<Void>> tasks = urls.stream()
        .map(url -> CompletableFuture.runAsync(() -> checkLink(url)))
        .toList();

CompletableFuture.allOf(tasks.toArray(new CompletableFuture[0])).join();

public static void checkLink(String url) {
    try {
        HttpURLConnection con = (HttpURLConnection) new URL(url).openConnection();
        con.setRequestMethod("GET");
        con.setConnectTimeout(5000);
        con.connect();
        System.out.println(url + " -> " + con.getResponseCode());
    } catch (Exception e) {
        System.out.println(url + " -> BROKEN");
    }
}

âœ” Why use this?

Non-blocking

Faster than thread pools

Easy to aggregate results

âœ… 4. Parallel Broken Link Testing with Selenium + Threads

If you want to test all <a> links on a webpage:

List<WebElement> links = driver.findElements(By.tagName("a"));

List<String> urls = links.stream()
        .map(e -> e.getAttribute("href"))
        .filter(Objects::nonNull)
        .toList();

urls.parallelStream().forEach(url -> {
    try {
        HttpURLConnection con = (HttpURLConnection) new URL(url).openConnection();
        con.setRequestMethod("GET");
        System.out.println(url + " -> " + con.getResponseCode());
    } catch (Exception e) {
        System.out.println(url + " -> BROKEN");
    }
});

âš¡ BONUS: RestAssured Version (Parallel)
urls.parallelStream().forEach(url -> {
    try {
        int status = given().get(url).statusCode();
        System.out.println(url + " -> " + status);
    } catch (Exception e) {
        System.out.println(url + " -> BROKEN");
    }
});

ðŸ”¥ Summary
Method	Best for	Difficulty
parallelStream()	50â€“200 links	Easy
ExecutorService	Heavy load, tuning	Medium
CompletableFuture	Fast, scalable	Medium
Selenium + parallelStream	Page link checking	Easy
RestAssured parallel	API links	Easy